text.html: Barnes mainly consists of affluent, middle-aged folk strolling along the river in boat shoes while chin-wagging over bagels. A welcome departure from the concrete metropolis, Barnes has green spaces, waterside walkways and dainty high streets to tide you over. Heck, we even managed to run into a Mustang-driving micro pig called Walter. Pack your best tweed, we're having it large (ish).

Best for… a Thames-view tummy filler

tip.text:
Step into Rick Stein and you'll easily see why locals swing by frequently enough to be welcomed on first name terms. The riverside setting and generously sized windows conspire to create an airy, relaxed space with gorgeous views of the Thames. Perfect for Boat Race day or a pre-Twickenham session.

The menu shifts with the seasons, aiming to keep dishes and ingredients fresh and relevant: iconic dishes such as the Dover sole à la Meunière and the Indonesian seafood curry are a fan favourite. A heads up: the wine list features many a fine vintage so don your best wine-tasting hat. If you’re in the mood for love then grab the window-seat in the conservatory - well romantic. Weekends are busy so book ahead.

text.text: Nothing relaxes the psyche like the sight of a flowing body of water, so what could be more pleasant and relaxing than grabbing a table in a lovely riverside restaurant and tucking into some seafood nosh? Rick Stein is a favourite of Barnes locals who pop their heads in for anything from a casual lunch to a wedding.
Best for... following in the footsteps of a legend (going for a walk)

tip.text:
Barnes’ very own Planet Earth: David Attenborough opened this wetland nature reserve in 2009 and it’s gone on to become an exceedingly popular destination for birdwatchers and school trips alike. If the sun is out then why not spend a couple of hours escaping the city? In this environment of ponds, ducks, otters and reeds you’ll forget all about the hustle and bustle of the tube.

Look, you won’t be blown away by the wildlife and the cafe is unremarkable to say the least. That being said, we dig people making an effort to look out for the environment and we’re the first to admit that the concrete jungle does get a tad stifling: a breath of fresh air is always welcome, even more so when it’s for a good cause (just don't hold that breath for anything spectacular).

Entry for adults is £13 with GiftAid, £12 without (last admission one hour before closing).

text.html: Everyone in the UK accepts that David Attenborough has the midas touch, so you’ll forgive us for getting excited about the gold plaque with his name on it outside this nature reserve. A place for wild things to be, well, wild - albeit not in a particularly exciting way. The cause is worthwhile even if the visit might not be. If you’re into binoculars, birds and the bemused looks of people trying to figure out what someone under the age of 40 (and over the age of 10) is doing here then absolutely get involved.

Best for… jazzing up your day out in Barnes

tip.text:
The Bull's Head was once a historic jazz pub. Then it became a Thai restaurant. Then it became a jazz pub again, and you can expect live music on the daily - gigs will typically set you back between £10 and £15, while the Saturday shows tend to be more rock-oriented and cost a fiver. The bar is well stocked with beers, wines and spirits to keep you swaying to the music.

Sunday roast at The Bull’s Head gets booked up weeks in advance, so we guess it’s worth a dabble. The upstairs rooms feature lovely views of the Thames - the TV in the balloon room can be hooked up to Sky, ideal for watching ruggers with the lads.

text.html: One probably wouldn’t expect to find a historic and cool jazz pub (or anything) in Barnes, would one? Well, apparently expectations can jog on ‘cos The Bull’s Head (or just The Bull for you swingin’ cats out there) was integral to the British jazz scene, rightly earning the ‘suburban Ronnie Scott’s’ tag. There was a brief stint as a Thai restaurant but Geronimo Inns have made an effort to restore this spot to the glory of days past.

tip.text:
Orange Pekoe is a bit of a suburban haven, cherished and loved by the locals, bringing Barnes the best loose leaf teas the world has to offer. If the colourful illustrations on the shopfront windows aren’t darling enough to have your head poking through the door then you’re a lost cause.

The space inside is small but made to seem all the bigger by the floods of natural light (all hail skylights), while vintage furniture, tabletops carved from trees and patterned wallpapers only enhance the cosiness. Cream tea is served all day for £8.95 while the hours between 2 and 5 pm are reserved for Traditional Afternoon Tea: finger-sandwiches, scones, cakes and a pot of tea or coffee for £19.95. Lovely.

text.html: Rule: you can’t expect to be taken seriously as a middle-class suburb if you don’t have a fancy tea room. There’s plenty to love about Orange Pekoe, from the colourful doodles decorating the shopfront to the vintage granny furniture. It’s a charming place to pass the meridian and why not broaden your loose leaf horizons in the meantime? Teas from around the world, but Afternoon Tea remains a distinctly British institution and we shall not be moved!

Best for… sunset sipping and romantic, riverside rendezvous-ing

tip.text:
A pub has sat on this gorgeous riverside plot since the 1600s and it’s hard to imagine a better spot for gripping a cold one and sitting out in the sun watching the boat race. That being said, it’s well cosy inside as well - ambient lighting, sofas and armchairs draped with rugs go some way to banishing any winter blues.

The restaurant upstairs boasts a seasonal menu (meat comes from a different farm every week), dishing up hearty, mouth-watering sharing plates: check out the 95oz rib of beef if you’re rolling through en masse. For all you lovers out there, table 6 is the most romantic seat in the house - privacy, armchairs, candles and all that jazz.

text.html: If a pub can keep you properly cosy through the winter, all crackling fires and rugs and whatnot, but still manage to offer up delightful outdoor drinking in the summer then we reckon it’s the real dealio. This is Barnes’ best riverside drinking spot: we were pretty blown away by the sight of the sun sinking into the Thames here in all its colourful glory (maybe Barnes ain’t so bad after all…).

tip.text:
Every neighbourhood has that one geezer that seems to have been knocking about forever. First opened in 1986, Sonny’s is that guy in Barnes: now co-owned by two star Michelin chef Phil Howard, the mission statement is filling up tums with classic dishes cooked with expertise. We especially like the sound of the chargrilled pluma of iberico pork with cavalo nero, roasted onion and pineapple relish.


Fancy throwing a bit of a fancy dinner? There’s a private dining room available for hire and all. You’ll find Sonny’s Foodstore next door, with deli-style snacks and bites up for grabs - they also offer a catering service for private hire.

text.html: The times are always a changing, and with changing times areas often wave goodbye to their more seasoned institutions - it makes us happy that Sonny’s Kitchen has been keeping this spot warm for 30 years now. Who said old dogs can’t learn new tricks? Sonny’s rebranded and even opened a lovely deli and everything: well 2016 - take that kidz.

Best for... a flick and some food

tip.text:
So you’re in Barnes and it’s raining - you’ve already exhausted the endless array of underground speakeasies and trendy coffee shops (cough) and you’re at a bit of a loss for things to do. Well nothing defeats a rainy day like the cinema, and a proper snazzy one goes a mighty long way (think plush seats and footrests).

You can drink in the company of legends at this popular spot, where everyone from the Rolling Stones to Hendricks has recorded. Also included in this historic building: a pastry kitchen, a swanky bar and an award-winning restaurant.

Best for… quizzing the night away (and a quick escape back across the river)

tip.text:
At The Bridge live music, open mic nights and pub quizzes feature on the schedule with much frequency; the quiz actually draws a full crowd on a weekly basis. Ales and lagers available are fairly standard and the wine list features old and new world bottles. The restaurant dishes up classic pub grub and features all the likely suspects, though none will blow your socks off.

The beer garden out back is large and will see a bar and BBQ installed in 2016, which should make for nice summer activity. Keep your eyes peeled inside for Howard - the mystical 94 year old drops in around 6pm every day and has been boozing at The Bridge for nigh on 60 years.

text.html: Also on the river (bit of a theme?), this restaurant-pub is full of stuff to remind you that you’re in a part of town somewhat fond of boats, racing, rivers and bridges. We hear the Wednesday pub quiz is an absolute riot, tables fully booked and all. Proximity to the bridge means Hammersmith can be sighted on the horizon and a quick escape from Barnes is on the cards if you fancy a change of scenery.

tip.text: If it's Thai food with serious kick you're after, Awesome Thai's your boy. It's inconspicuously situated in SW London's quaint and unassuming Barnes, with a rather bland exterior, but fresh, luscious grub inside. Menu highlights include the 'pla hor bai teoy' (grilled fish fillet wrapped in pandan leaves served with special house sauce) and the 'tom yum seafood soup'. After all, what's better than the light, nourishing zing of tom yum come winter?

text.text: If it's Thai food with serious kick you're after, Awesome Thai's the one. It might have a pretty bland exterior, but the food is actually pretty decent -  menu highlights include the 'pla hor bai teoy' (grilled fish fillet wrapped in pandan leaves served with special house sauce) and the 'tom yum seafood soup'. Also pretty affordable for this part of town.
